26// -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
27// Registers and FPURegisters.
28
29// Number of general purpose registers.
30const int kNumRegisters = 32;
31const int kInvalidRegister = -1;
32
33// Number of registers with pc.
34const int kNumSimuRegisters = 33;
35
36// In the simulator, the PC register is simulated as the 33th register.
37const int kPCRegister = 32;
38
39// Number of floating point registers.
40const int kNumFPURegisters = 32;
41const int kInvalidFPURegister = -1;
42
43// FPU control registers.
44const int kFCSRRegister = 0;
45const int kInvalidFPUControlRegister = -1;
46const uint32_t kFPUInvalidResult = static_cast<uint32_t>(1u << 31) - 1;
47const int32_t kFPUInvalidResultNegative = static_cast<int32_t>(1u << 31);
48const uint64_t kFPU64InvalidResult =
49 static_cast<uint64_t>(static_cast<uint64_t>(1) << 63) - 1;
50const int64_t kFPU64InvalidResultNegative =
51 static_cast<int64_t>(static_cast<uint64_t>(1) << 63);
52
53// FCSR constants.
54const uint32_t kFCSRInexactCauseBit = 24;
55const uint32_t kFCSRUnderflowCauseBit = 25;
56const uint32_t kFCSROverflowCauseBit = 26;
57const uint32_t kFCSRDivideByZeroCauseBit = 27;
58const uint32_t kFCSRInvalidOpCauseBit = 28;
59
60const uint32_t kFCSRInexactCauseMask = 1 << kFCSRInexactCauseBit;
61const uint32_t kFCSRUnderflowCauseMask = 1 << kFCSRUnderflowCauseBit;
62const uint32_t kFCSROverflowCauseMask = 1 << kFCSROverflowCauseBit;
63const uint32_t kFCSRDivideByZeroCauseMask = 1 << kFCSRDivideByZeroCauseBit;
64const uint32_t kFCSRInvalidOpCauseMask = 1 << kFCSRInvalidOpCauseBit;
65
66const uint32_t kFCSRCauseMask =
67 kFCSRInexactCauseMask | kFCSRUnderflowCauseMask | kFCSROverflowCauseMask |
68 kFCSRDivideByZeroCauseMask | kFCSRInvalidOpCauseMask;
69
70const uint32_t kFCSRExceptionCauseMask = kFCSRCauseMask ^ kFCSRInexactCauseMask;
71
72// Actual value of root register is offset from the root array's start
73// to take advantage of negative displacement values.
74constexpr int kRootRegisterBias = 256;

76// Helper functions for converting between register numbers and names.
77class Registers {
78 public:
79 // Return the name of the register.
80 static const char* Name(int reg);
81
82 // Lookup the register number for the name provided.
83 static int Number(const char* name);
84
85 struct RegisterAlias {
86 int reg;
87 const char* name;
88 };
89

92
93 private:

95 static const RegisterAlias aliases_[];
96};

123// Special Software Interrupt codes when used in the presence of the LOONG64
124// simulator.
125enum SoftwareInterruptCodes {
126 // Transition to C code.
127 call_rt_redirected = 0x7fff
128};
129
130// On LOONG64 Simulator breakpoints can have different codes:
131// - Breaks between 0 and kMaxWatchpointCode are treated as simple watchpoints,
132// the simulator will run through them and print the registers.
133// - Breaks between kMaxWatchpointCode and kMaxStopCode are treated as stop()
134// instructions (see Assembler::stop()).
135// - Breaks larger than kMaxStopCode are simple breaks, dropping you into the
136// debugger.
137const uint32_t kMaxWatchpointCode = 31;
138const uint32_t kMaxStopCode = 127;
139static_assert(kMaxWatchpointCode < kMaxStopCode);
140

533// ----- Emulated conditions.
534// On LOONG64 we use this enum to abstract from conditional branch instructions.
535// The 'U' prefix is used to specify unsigned comparisons.
536enum Condition : int {
537 overflow = 0,
538 no_overflow = 1,
539 Uless = 2,
540 Ugreater_equal = 3,
541 Uless_equal = 4,
542 Ugreater = 5,
543 equal = 6,
544 not_equal = 7, // Unordered or Not Equal.
545 negative = 8,
546 positive = 9,
547 parity_even = 10,
548 parity_odd = 11,
549 less = 12,
550 greater_equal = 13,
551 less_equal = 14,
552 greater = 15,
553 ueq = 16, // Unordered or Equal.
554 ogl = 17, // Ordered and Not Equal.
555 cc_always = 18,
556
557 // Aliases.
558 carry = Uless,
559 not_carry = Ugreater_equal,
560 zero = equal,
561 eq = equal,
562 not_zero = not_equal,
563 ne = not_equal,
564 nz = not_equal,
565 sign = negative,
566 not_sign = positive,
567 mi = negative,
568 pl = positive,
569 hi = Ugreater,
570 ls = Uless_equal,
571 ge = greater_equal,
572 lt = less,
573 gt = greater,
574 le = less_equal,
575 hs = Ugreater_equal,
576 lo = Uless,
577 al = cc_always,
578 ult = Uless,
579 uge = Ugreater_equal,
580 ule = Uless_equal,
581 ugt = Ugreater,
582
583 // Unified cross-platform condition names/aliases.
584 kEqual = equal,
585 kNotEqual = not_equal,
586 kLessThan = less,
587 kGreaterThan = greater,
588 kLessThanEqual = less_equal,
589 kGreaterThanEqual = greater_equal,
590 kUnsignedLessThan = Uless,
591 kUnsignedGreaterThan = Ugreater,
592 kUnsignedLessThanEqual = Uless_equal,
593 kUnsignedGreaterThanEqual = Ugreater_equal,
594 kOverflow = overflow,
595 kNoOverflow = no_overflow,
596 kZero = equal,
597 kNotZero = not_equal,
598};
599
600// Returns the equivalent of !cc.
601inline Condition NegateCondition(Condition cc) {
602 DCHECK(cc != cc_always);
603 return static_cast<Condition>(cc ^ 1);
604}

606inline Condition NegateFpuCondition(Condition cc) {
607 DCHECK(cc != cc_always);
608 switch (cc) {
609 case ult:
610 return ge;
611 case ugt:
612 return le;
613 case uge:
614 return lt;
615 case ule:
616 return gt;
617 case lt:
618 return uge;
619 case gt:
620 return ule;
621 case ge:
622 return ult;
623 case le:
624 return ugt;
625 case eq:
626 return ne;
627 case ne:
628 return eq;
629 case ueq:
630 return ogl;
631 case ogl:
632 return ueq;
633 default:
634 return cc;
635 }
636}

669// FPU rounding modes.
670enum FPURoundingMode {

672 RZ = 0b01 << kFPURoundingModeShift, // Round towards zero.
673 RP = 0b10 << kFPURoundingModeShift, // Round towards Plus Infinity.
674 RM = 0b11 << kFPURoundingModeShift, // Round towards Minus Infinity.

678 kRoundToZero = RZ,
679 kRoundToPlusInf = RP,
680 kRoundToMinusInf = RM,

684 mode_floor = RM,

719class InstructionBase {
720 public:
721 enum Type {
722 kOp6Type,
723 kOp7Type,
724 kOp8Type,
725 kOp10Type,
726 kOp12Type,
727 kOp14Type,
728 kOp17Type,
729 kOp22Type,
730 kUnsupported = -1
731 };
732
733 // Get the raw instruction bits.
734 inline Instr InstructionBits() const {
735 return *reinterpret_cast<const Instr*>(this);
736 }
737
738 // Set the raw instruction bits to value.
739 inline void SetInstructionBits(Instr value) {
740 *reinterpret_cast<Instr*>(this) = value;
741 }
742
743 // Read one particular bit out of the instruction bits.
744 inline int Bit(int nr) const { return (InstructionBits() >> nr) & 1; }
745
746 // Read a bit field out of the instruction bits.
747 inline int Bits(int hi, int lo) const {
748 return (InstructionBits() >> lo) & ((2U << (hi - lo)) - 1);
749 }
750
751 // Safe to call within InstructionType().
752 inline int RjFieldRawNoAssert() const {
753 return InstructionBits() & kRjFieldMask;
754 }
755
756 // Get the encoding type of the instruction.
757 inline Type InstructionType() const;
758
759 protected:
760 InstructionBase() {}
761};

917class Instruction : public InstructionGetters<InstructionBase> {
918 public:
919 // Instructions are read of out a code stream. The only way to get a
920 // reference to an instruction is to convert a pointer. There is no way
921 // to allocate or create instances of class Instruction.
922 // Use the At(pc) function to create references to Instruction.
923 static Instruction* At(uint8_t* pc) {
924 return reinterpret_cast<Instruction*>(pc);
925 }

927 private:
928 // We need to prevent the creation of instances of class Instruction.
929 DISALLOW_IMPLICIT_CONSTRUCTORS(Instruction);
930};

939InstructionBase::Type InstructionBase::InstructionType() const {
940 InstructionBase::Type kType = kUnsupported;
941
942 // Check for kOp6Type
943 switch (Bits(31, 26) << 26) {
944 case ADDU16I_D:
945 case BEQZ:
946 case BNEZ:
947 case BCZ:
948 case JIRL:
949 case B:
950 case BL:
951 case BEQ:
952 case BNE:
953 case BLT:
954 case BGE:
955 case BLTU:
956 case BGEU:
957 kType = kOp6Type;
958 break;
959 default:
960 kType = kUnsupported;
961 }
962
963 if (kType == kUnsupported) {
964 // Check for kOp7Type
965 switch (Bits(31, 25) << 25) {
966 case LU12I_W:
967 case LU32I_D:
968 case PCADDI:
969 case PCALAU12I:
970 case PCADDU12I:
971 case PCADDU18I:
972 kType = kOp7Type;
973 break;
974 default:
975 kType = kUnsupported;
976 }
977 }
978
979 if (kType == kUnsupported) {
980 // Check for kOp8Type
981 switch (Bits(31, 24) << 24) {
982 case LDPTR_W:
983 case STPTR_W:
984 case LDPTR_D:
985 case STPTR_D:
986 case LL_W:
987 case SC_W:
988 case LL_D:
989 case SC_D:
990 kType = kOp8Type;
991 break;
992 default:
993 kType = kUnsupported;
994 }
995 }
996
997 if (kType == kUnsupported) {
998 // Check for kOp10Type
999 switch (Bits(31, 22) << 22) {
1000 case BSTR_W: {
1001 // If Bit(21) = 0, then the Opcode is not BSTR_W.
1002 if (Bit(21) == 0)
1003 kType = kUnsupported;

1005 kType = kOp10Type;
1006 break;
1007 }
1008 case BSTRINS_D:
1009 case BSTRPICK_D:

1024 case ST_W:
1025 case ST_D:

1027 case LD_HU:

1030 case FST_S:

1032 case FST_D:

1036 kType = kUnsupported;
1037 }
1038 }

1040 if (kType == kUnsupported) {
1041 // Check for kOp12Type
